    "Let me analyze the mapped transformation to identify the reaction center.\n\nReactants:\n1. CC1=C[C:20](=[O:21])CCC1 - This is a cyclohexenone (2-cyclohexen-1-one) with a methyl group. The mapped atoms are C:20 and O:21, which form a carbonyl group (C=O).\n\n2. COCC1CCCN1[NH2:10] - This is an amino compound with NH2:10 as the mapped nitrogen.\n\nProducts:\nCC1=C[C:20](CCC1)([NH2+:10]N2CCCC2COC)[O-:21]\n\nSo in the product:\n- C:20 is now bonded to CCC1 (the ring), [NH2+:10]N2CCCC2COC, and [O-:21]\n- O:21 is now O- (negatively charged)\n- NH2:10 is now NH2+:10 (positively charged) and bonded to N2CCCC2COC\n\nThe transformation is:\n- The C=O double bond (C:20=O:21) becomes C:20-O:21 single bond (with O:21 becoming O-)\n- NH2:10 adds to C:20, forming C:20-[NH2+:10]\n- The nitrogen NH2:10 becomes NH2+:10 (protonated/charged)\n- The second nitrogen (from the aziridine-like ring N1CCCC1COC) connects to NH2+:10\n\nWait, let me re-read more carefully.\n\nReactant 2: COCC1CCCN1[NH2:10]\nThis has a ring: N1CCCC1 with COC attached, and [NH2:10] attached to N1.\n\nSo the structure is: COC-CH2-CH2-CH2-CH2-N(-NH2)-ring closure\n\nProduct: [NH2+:10]N2CCCC2COC\nSo NH2+:10 is bonded to N2, and N2CCCC2COC forms a ring.\n\nThe key transformation at the reaction center:\n1. C:20=O:21 (carbonyl) → C:20-[O-:21] (enolate-like, single bond)\n2. NH2:10 adds to C:20 → C:20-[NH2+:10]\n3. NH2:10 becomes NH2+:10 (gains positive charge)\n\nThis is essentially an amination of a carbonyl - the amine (NH2) attacks the carbonyl carbon, breaking the C=O double bond to form a C-N bond and converting C=O to C-O- (enolate). The nitrogen gets protonated to become NH2+.\n\nThe reaction center involves:\n- Bond change: C:20=O:21 → C:20-O:21 (double bond to single bond)\n- Bond formed: C:20-[NH2+:10] (new bond between C:20 and N:10)\n- Charge change: O:21 neutral → O:21 negative (O-)\n- Charge change: NH2:10 neutral → NH2+:10 positive\n\nThis is a nucleophilic addition of an amine to a carbonyl (enamine/imine formation pathway, but stopped at the carbinolamine stage with proton transfer).\n\nThe reaction center: C:20=O:21 double bond breaks to single bond, new bond C:20-N:10 forms, O:21 gains negative charge, N:10 gains positive charge.\n\nLet me format this as a reaction edit summary:\n\nBond edits:\n- Break: C:20=O:21 (double → single)\n- Form: C:20-[NH2+:10] (new single bond)\n\nCharge edits:\n- O:21: 0 → -1\n- N:10 (in NH2): 0 → +1\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the product structure:\n\nCC1=C[C:20](CCC1)([NH2+:10]N2CCCC2COC)[O-:21]\n\nThe C:20 has four bonds: to CCC1 (ring), to [NH2+:10]N2CCCC2COC, to [O-:21], and to C=C (the double bond part of the ring).\n\nWait - CC1=C[C:20]... means there's a double bond C=C in the ring, and C:20 is part of the ring. So C:20 is the carbon at position 1 of the cyclohexenone ring.\n\nIn the reactant: CC1=C[C:20](=[O:21])CCC1\nThis means C:20 has a double bond to O:21 (the carbonyl) and is part of the ring with a C=C double bond adjacent.\n\nIn the product: CC1=C[C:20](CCC1)([NH2+:10]N2CCCC2COC)[O-:21]\nC:20 now has single bonds to: CCC1 (ring portion), [NH2+:10]N2CCCC2COC, and [O-:21]. The C=C in the ring remains.\n\nSo the reaction center is:\n1. C:20=O:21 double bond → C:20-O:21 single bond (O:21 becomes O-)\n2. New bond formed: C:20-N:10 (N:10 becomes NH2+)\n\nThis is nucleophilic addition of amine to carbonyl.\n\nReaction edit summary format:\n- Bond_break: C:20=O:21\n- Bond_form: C:20-N:10\n- Charge_change: O:21 (0→-1), N:10 (0→+1)\n\nLet me provide this in a compact format."
